data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider already didn't support sync APIs natively — it shimmed them via **sync-over-async** (blocking on `Task.Result`). You opted in with something like:

```csharp
options.UseCosmos(...).ConfigureWarnings(w =>
    w.Ignore(CosmosEventId.SyncNotSupported));
```

**In .NET 11 (EF Core 11), that opt-in is removed entirely.** Every synchronous call — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, `SaveChanges()` — will throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime. There is no workaround; the Cosmos provider is async-only.

## The fix

Convert to async all the way through:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return types become `Task<T>` / `Task`
- Methods are marked `async` and use `await`
- Sync operators → async variants (`ToListAsync`, `FirstAsync`, `CountAsync`, `SaveChangesAsync`)
- Callers must also be updated to `await` these methods (async propagates up the call stack)

> ⚠️ Don't be tempted to call `.Result` or `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` on the returned tasks — that's the same sync-over-async antipattern and risks deadlocks.
